\begin{enumerate}
\item Given an array $A$ of length $n$ containing integers, describe an algorithm that checks whether there exists a pair of distinct elements whose difference in values equals their distance in the array. In other words, determine whether there exist indices $i<j$ such that $|a_j - a_i| = j - i$.
\item Now assume the numbers come from the domain $\{-n^2, \ldots, n^2\}$. Describe the most efficient algorithm in the worst case. For the avoidance of doubt, the algorithm should use linear space.
\end{enumerate}

Describe a data structure whose elements are pairs of keys $(a,b)$ such that every left key in a pair is an integer belonging to the range $[1,10n]$. You may assume that all key pairs are distinct. The data structure must support the following operations (where $n$ is the number of key pairs currently in the data structure):
\begin{itemize}
\item \textsc{Insert}$(a,b)$ — insert the key pair $(a,b)$ into the data structure. The operation must run in amortized time $O(1)$.
\item \textsc{IncreaseKey}$((a,b),x)$ — given a pointer to a key pair $(a,b)$ currently in the data structure and a positive number $x$, increase the right key by $x$. The operation must run in amortized time $O(1)$.
\item \textsc{Delete}$((a,b))$ — given a pointer to a key pair $(a,b)$ currently in the data structure, delete it. The operation must run in amortized time $O(\log n)$.
\end{itemize}

We now modify the operation $\mathrm{Insert}(D,x)$ so that it receives an additional parameter $i$ as follows:
\begin{itemize}
\item $\mathrm{Insert}(D,i,x)$ inserts $x$ into the data structure with index $i$ (assume that $i$ is at least $1$, and that it is less than or equal to the number of elements in $D$ plus $1$). That is, the index of an element in the data structure is not determined by the serial number of the $\mathrm{Insert}$ operation that inserted it, but directly by the additional parameter. Note that inserting an element with index $i$ increases by $1$ the indices of the elements whose index is greater than or equal to $i$.
\end{itemize}

(c) Describe a deterministic data structure in which $\mathrm{Insert}(D,i,x)$ takes $O(\log(i+1))$ amortized time, $\mathrm{FindByIndex}(D,i)$ takes $O(\log(i+1))$ time in the worst case and amortized, and $\mathrm{FindByKey}(D,k)$ takes $O(n)$ time in the worst case and amortized. The space used by the data structure should be $O(n)$.

Describe an implementation of a data structure with the following operations (\(x\) is a key):
\begin{itemize}
\item Insert(\(x\)) — amortized time \(O(\log n)\).
\item Search(\(x\)) — amortized time \(O(\log n)\).
\item Delete(\(x\)) — amortized time \(O(1)\) and worst-case time \(O(1)\).
\end{itemize}
